1. Ensure the login view renders correctly without Razor interpreting an inline email-like literal.
2. Locate the input placeholder that contains a literal '@' (e.g., "<username>@ff.com").
3. Escape the '@' for Razor by doubling it ("@@") so Razor emits a single '@' in the HTML output.
4. Keep all existing Razor expressions (usings, site settings, DateTime, etc.) unchanged.
5. Output the full .cshtml file with the placeholder updated to use "@@".

Implementation details:
- Use Razor comment block to include this pseudocode at the top (safe, will not render).
- Replace placeholder attribute value to: "for AD Authentication: <username>@@ff.com"
- Leave other Razor expressions intact.
